task: How to remove objects from an image in PhotoShop?

subtitles.text: Today, you'll learn how to remove objects in Photoshop with ease, even when you're working with complex photos.
This technique is one that can work as a standalone method, but can be enhanced with the help of other object removal tools, as you'll learn later in the lesson.

Now, we're going to cover a lot in this video, so if you want to make sure that all these techniques stick, be sure to download the free lesson cheat sheet for this video available in the description below.
Now, in this example, we're going to remove this car from the background, some of the cars down the street, and then we're going to touch things up with a few additional tools to finalize the result.

Now, typically, with object removal tools, something as large as this car would be extremely, extremely difficult to remove, because we don't have enough sample areas to rebuild what was behind this car.
But now, with Generative Fill, we can easily create new pixels within this photo to replace whatever was behind this car, or at least make it look like we have replaced it.
So, the first thing we need to do in this process is select the Lasso tool.
To select the Lasso tool, just press L on your keyboard, or you can find it right here inside of the toolbar.
The reason I'm choosing the Lasso tool is because it's really easy to create a general selection around the object that you're trying to replace with Generative Fill.
From there, we have a couple important settings up in the Options bar.
I'll set the feather to 10 pixels, and then make sure that AntiAliased is checked.
Now, we can go and create a selection around the object that we want to remove, which, in this case, is the car.
So, I'll go and click and drag around the entire car, just outside of the edge, and that also includes this bumper that is between this gentleman's legs here.

So, I'm going to go all the way around, like so, just around the outside edges of the car, giving enough breathing room, so Photoshop can figure out what actually needs to fill in this selection area.
With this active selection, we can just go and click on Generative Fill inside of the Contextual taskbar.
If you don't see this, just go up to Window, and then down here to the Contextual taskbar to reveal it.
So, going ahead and clicking on Generative Fill, we'll then go and click Generate without any specific prompt added.
Photoshop will take a minute to load the results, and then it will give us three variations here inside of the Properties panel that we can click between to see which option we like the best.
Now, this one looks pretty decent, but the post is in a weird area, so I don't really like how that turned out.
I don't like the way this curb is looking here either, so we're actually going to regenerate a few different results for us because all three of these didn't really work out in our favor.
So, again, I'll go ahead and click on Generate to create a new set of options for us to choose from.
Now, as you can see, we have a new row of variations that we can click between to choose something that we like.
In this case, this example actually looks pretty good to me, or even this one here is pretty acceptable as well.
I think I'm going to opt for this particular one instead.
I think it looks the most seamless overall rather than having to regenerate something else for the sake of example.
So, now all of those adjustments were applied onto a new generative fill layer that if I turn this on and off, you can see the before and after.
So, what has happened here is that it rebuilt our subject's pants that I don't really like, but we'll touch this up in just a moment.
But most importantly, it did a great job to fill in all of this detail that was once behind the car.
This would be nearly impossible to replicate with any of the previous object removal tools in Photoshop like the Clone Stamp tool or the Remove tool for example.
This is like taking things to a totally new level.
Now, before we go and touch up the problem areas, I'm also going to go and remove these cars from the background.

So, once again, still with the Lasso tool selected, I'll just click and drag around those cars in the background that I want to remove with the same settings as before so that 10 pixel feather antialias is checked.

Once again, I'll click on Generative Fill in the contextual taskbar, then click on Generate while that selection is active and Photoshop will take a minute to load and then fill in that active selection area with something new.
Now, with that complete, we can click between our variations until we have something that we're happy with.
In this case, the second variation looks best to me, so I'm going to select that one here and again, it's on its own generative fill layer.

So, now with this complete, we have to go through and touch up any other smaller areas that we would like to remove as well as fix any problems that we have created within our generative fill layers, such as the top of our subject's leg, for example.
Before we get to touching up the leg, we're going to go and remove some of the people in the background of this photo just to make it totally clean.

But because these are relatively small areas of the photo, rather than having to use all the computing power and slow down your computer for generative fill, we can just use something like the Remove tool to touch this up.
Clicking on the New Layer icon to create a new layer at the top of our layer stack.
I'll call this layer to Remove tool.
I'll now go ahead and select the Remove tool from the toolbar here and then make sure that Sample All Layers is enabled.

From there, I can just go and paint over the subject that I would like to remove or the person in the background and then because I have remove after each brush stroke unchecked, I'm going to go and paint over the next person I want to remove from the background as well.
With those two pink highlights added, I'll press Enter and now Photoshop will remove those from my photo super easily.
If you want to learn more about the Remove tool specifically, you could check out this video right here where I dive deep into how to use that tool.
So now the final thing we have to do is touch up our subject's leg because if I zoom in here, you can see how he kind of has like this bent thigh.
It looks like he has a broken leg or something.
So what we need to do is create a selection of the original leg to restore it and then we need to touch up the outer edges once again.
It sounds a bit complicated, but I promise you it's super easy.
So holding Alt or Option, I'll click on the eyeball icon beside my image layer so that now I'm only viewing that layer.
With that particular image layer selected, I'm going to go and select the Object Selection tool up here in the toolbar.
With the mode set to Lasso, I'm going to click and drag around the area that I want to restore which is my subject's leg.
So just click and drag just around the outside edges of that leg like so and then it will snap to the edge of that object.
Now with this selection active, I'm going to reenable all of my previous layers by clicking and dragging through the eyeball icons to make them visible once again.
Now to restore the contents of this selection area, we need to remove it from our generative fill layer that is causing this problem.
So clicking on the generative fill layer that is the one that is removing that car and creating the issue with the leg, I'll click on that layer mask while I have this active selection.
I'll then grab my brush tool by pressing B and set my foreground color to black.
Now with that generative fill layer mask selected, I can just go and paint inside of this selection area and it's going to restore that leg for me.
Now, of course, I still have some areas outside of the selection that are showing through from this generative fill layer.
So what we're going to do is invert this selection and then mask out these additional problem areas.
So within the contextual taskbar, we can just click on the invert selection option and now we're selecting everything outside of our subject's leg.
And with that generative fill layer mask still selected, my foreground color is still set to black, I can now go and just mask out any of those other problem areas around my subject's leg.
Now it is going to reveal the car back into view because that is what was being removed with the generative fill layer, but we can easily go and refine this using a couple of different tools.
So now with this complete, I'm going to leave this selection active and then touch up the outside edge of this leg using the remove tool.

So once again, going to the remove tool layer, I'm going to select the remove tool by pressing J and then with the sample all layers enabled, remove after each brush stroke disabled, I'll click and drag over this part of the car like so, and I'll only be able to select outside of the edge of my subject's leg because of this active selection.
I'll press enter to commit to those changes and Photoshop will automatically remove that for me.
Now for this remaining area between my subject's legs, I'll press command or control D to deselect this and we'll just use another generative fill layer to make our life nice and easy.

With the lasso tool selected by pressing L, I'll just create a much smaller and specific selection area around my subject's leg so that Photoshop has an easier time to only remove the things that we don't want and it won't really mess up the edges of his pants that we do want to maintain.
So with this selection active, we'll click on generative fill just like before.
We'll then click on generate with no specific prompt added to that generative fill adjustment.
Once again, we have a few different variations that we can choose between but the first one seems to be my favorite.
So I'll just click on that variation to enable it.
Now zooming out, you can see that we have successfully removed the car from the photo, the cars in the background, the people from the sidewalk and we have maintained the look of our subject.
So looking at our before and after, it's pretty crazy how much we were able to remove with relatively little effort all because of the help of generative fill.
This is by far one of my favorite new object removal adjustment options and it is something that you should definitely use when you're trying to remove larger things from your images.

Now again, if you want to download the free PDF lesson cheat sheet for this video, just click the link in the description below, type in your name and email, click the button and you'll instantly receive a nice new PDF guide in your inbox.
You'll also be added to the list of people waiting for all my future PDF guides.
So you only have to do this process once and then you're good to go.
But now if you're looking for ways to take your object removal skills in Photoshop even further, be sure to check out this next video here covering the best tools for object removal in Photoshop.
It's a great way to continue to expand on the object removal skills you learned here and I hope to see you there next.

steps: Open the image in Photoshop.
Select the Lasso tool by pressing 'L' on your keyboard or finding it in the toolbar.
Set the feather to 10 pixels and ensure Anti-Aliased is checked in the Options bar.
Create a selection around the object you want to remove, leaving some space around it.
Click on 'Generative Fill' in the Contextual taskbar and then click 'Generate' without adding a prompt.
Review the variations provided and select the one that looks best.
Repeat the process for any other large objects you want to remove.
For smaller areas, use the Remove tool by creating a new layer and enabling 'Sample All Layers'.
Paint over the areas you want to remove with the Remove tool and press Enter to apply changes.
To fix any issues with the generative fill, use the Object Selection tool to select the area you want to restore.
With the selection active, mask out the problem areas on the generative fill layer using a brush with the foreground color set to black.
Invert the selection to mask out additional problem areas if needed.
Use the Remove tool to touch up any remaining areas outside the selection.
For final adjustments, use the Lasso tool to create a smaller selection and apply Generative Fill again.
Review the final image to ensure all unwanted objects are removed and the image looks seamless.

Once again, we have a few different variations that we can choose between but the first one seems to be my favorite. So I'll just click on that variation to enable it. Now zooming out, you can see that we have successfully removed the car from the photo, the cars in the background, the people from the sidewalk and we have maintained the look of our subject. So looking at our before and after, it's pretty crazy how much we were able to remove with relatively little effort all because of the help of generative fill. This is by far one of my favorite new object removal adjustment options and it is something that you should definitely use when you're trying to remove larger things from your images. Now again, if you want to download the free PDF lesson cheat sheet for this video, just click the link in the description below, type in your name and email, click the button and you'll instantly receive a nice new PDF guide in your inbox. You'll also be added to the list of people waiting for all my future PDF guides. So you only have to do this process once and then you're good to go. But now if you're looking for ways to take your object removal skills in Photoshop even further, be sure to check out this next video here covering the best tools for object removal in Photoshop. It's a great way to continue to expand on the object removal skills you learned here and I hope to see you there next.

subgoal_summaries.title: Open Image-0
outcome: Image is open in Photoshop
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Open the image file in Photoshop.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: To begin the process of removing objects from the image, you need to have the image open in Photoshop.

subgoal_summaries.title: Select Object-1
outcome: The Lasso tool is selected, ready to create a selection around the object to be removed.
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Select the Lasso tool by pressing 'L' on your keyboard or finding it in the toolbar.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: The Lasso tool is chosen because it allows for easy creation of a general selection around the object to be replaced with Generative Fill.

subgoal_summaries.title: Refine Selection-2
materials: Photoshop software with an image loaded
outcome: The Lasso tool is configured with a feather of 10 pixels and Anti-Aliased option enabled, ready for making a selection.
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Set the feather to 10 pixels and ensure Anti-Aliased is checked in the Options bar.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Setting the feather to 10 pixels ensures that the edges of the selection are soft, which helps in blending the filled area with the surrounding pixels. Enabling Anti-Aliased ensures that the edges of the selection are smooth, preventing jagged edges.

subgoal_summaries.title: Select Object-1
outcome: A selection around the object to be removed with some space around it
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Select the Lasso tool and create a selection around the object you want to remove, leaving some space around it.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Leaving space around the object helps Photoshop determine what needs to fill in the selection area.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Set the feather to 10 pixels and ensure AntiAliased is checked for smoother selection edges.

subgoal_summaries.title: Remove Object-4
materials: An image with an object to remove
outcome: The object in the image is removed and replaced with generated content
Three variations of the filled area are provided for selection
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Click on 'Generative Fill' in the Contextual taskbar and then click 'Generate' without adding a prompt.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Generative Fill creates new pixels to replace the selected area, providing multiple variations to choose from.
subgoal_summaries.tips: If the Contextual taskbar is not visible, go to Window and select Contextual taskbar to reveal it.

subgoal_summaries.title: Review and Adjust-5
materials: Photoshop software with Generative Fill feature
outcome: Selected the best variation for object removal
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Review the variations provided in the Properties panel and select the one that looks best.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Selecting the best variation ensures that the object removal looks seamless and natural in the image.
subgoal_summaries.tips: If none of the variations look good, you can regenerate new options by clicking on Generate again.

subgoal_summaries.title: Repeat Process-6
outcome: All large objects that need to be removed from the image are successfully removed.
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Repeat the process of selecting the Lasso tool, creating a selection around the large object, and using Generative Fill to remove it.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: This process allows you to remove large objects from the image by generating new pixels to fill the selection area, making it appear as if the object was never there.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Ensure the feather is set to 10 pixels and AntiAliased is checked for smooth selection edges. Use the variations provided by Generative Fill to choose the best result.

subgoal_summaries.title: Touch Up-7
outcome: Smaller areas and people in the background are removed from the image.
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Create a new layer and enable 'Sample All Layers'. Select the Remove tool and paint over the areas you want to remove. Press Enter to apply the changes.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Using the Remove tool on a new layer with 'Sample All Layers' enabled allows for non-destructive editing and ensures that the tool samples from all visible layers to make the removal seamless.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Ensure 'Sample All Layers' is enabled for the Remove tool to work effectively across all layers. Disable 'Remove after each brush stroke' for continuous painting.

subgoal_summaries.title: Review and Adjust-5
outcome: Restored problem areas on the generative fill layer
Masked out additional problem areas
subgoal_summaries.instructions: To fix any issues with the generative fill, use the Object Selection tool to select the area you want to restore. With the selection active, mask out the problem areas on the generative fill layer using a brush with the foreground color set to black. Invert the selection to mask out additional problem areas if needed.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: This process is performed to restore the original content in areas where the generative fill has caused issues, such as distorting parts of the image that should remain unchanged.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Ensure the foreground color is set to black when masking out areas on the generative fill layer. Use the invert selection option to easily select areas outside the current selection.

subgoal_summaries.title: Touch Up-7
materials: Photoshop software with an image loaded
outcome: Smaller areas and problem areas in the image are touched up and cleaned.
Unwanted objects or people in the background are removed.
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Select the Remove tool from the toolbar, ensure 'Sample All Layers' is enabled, and paint over the areas you want to remove. Press Enter to apply the changes.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: The Remove tool is used for smaller areas to avoid using too much computing power, which can slow down the computer when using Generative Fill.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Ensure 'Sample All Layers' is enabled for the Remove tool to work across all layers. Disable 'Remove after each brush stroke' to paint over multiple areas before applying changes.

subgoal_summaries.title: Review and Adjust-5
outcome: Final image with all unwanted objects removed and a seamless appearance
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Use the Lasso tool to create a smaller selection around the area needing adjustment and apply Generative Fill again. Review the final image to ensure all unwanted objects are removed and the image looks seamless.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Creating a smaller selection helps Photoshop focus on the specific area to remove unwanted elements without affecting desired parts of the image. Reviewing the final image ensures that all adjustments have been made correctly and the image appears natural.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Ensure the selection is precise to avoid altering parts of the image you want to keep. Choose the best variation from Generative Fill results for a seamless look.

metadata.title: The EASIEST Way To Remove Objects In Photoshop

subtitles.text: Welcome to the Photoshop in 5 series, where today, in less than 5 minutes, I'll teach you how to remove unwanted subjects or objects from your photos in 3 simple steps.
Selection, removal and touch up.
First, we're going to start with some easy to use selection methods.
That way, no matter the job, you're always going to have a method to remove your subjects.
The first is the quick selection tool, or W. Simply select around the subject or object you want to remove, and Photoshop will select what is inside.
This works best with space around it.
Second is the lasso tool, or L. This is good if you have a steady hand and for smaller or simple subjects, simply draw around them.
If you need to move the canvas whilst you're doing this, hold down left click and hold spacebar at the same time to move the canvas.
The polygonal lasso tool, or L, works the same, but with straight lines you click between, and is a little more forgiving if your path is not quite right.
You can also hold spacebar to move the canvas.
Third, we have the quick mask mode.
Hit this button to activate it, then select the paintbrush or hit B. Everything will be painted transparent red, and this shows what we are selecting.
Make sure that the hardness is 100, opacity is 100 and flow is 100.
You can find these settings in the option bar located at the top of the screen.
To adjust your brush size, hold alt, right click and slide left or right to change it.
You can also go up to the options panel to change it as well.
Now you can paint over your subject.
Remember we are making sure, if possible, to leave a little bit of space.
When you are finished, hit the quick mask mode button again and your painting will become a selection.
We want to invert our selection, so simply press shift, control and I at the same time, and our selection is ready to go.
The final method is the pen tool, or P. Simply click to drop a point.
When you drop another point, the two will connect.
You can hold and drag on your new point to make the line curved.
Hold the alt button and press on the middle of the curved point if you want to continue with a straight line instead for your next point.
If you don't, the line will continue in its natural curve when you make your next point.
This tool has so many options and cool features, so be sure to check out one of Photoshop's other amazing tutorials to learn even more about the pen tool.
Once finished, go to paths, control click the path in the box and your path will become a selection.
Now I'll show you how to expand the selection for those methods that don't leave space around the selection.
You can simply go to select, modify, expand.
The number will depend on how big your image is. 15 should work well for this image and your selection now has some room to make filling it even smoother.
Now let me show you where the magic happens with the content aware fill tool.
For the automatic option, hit control backspace to bring up the fill panel.
Set the contents to content aware fill.
Make sure colour adaptation is ticked and hit ok to let Photoshop do its magic.
How incredible is that result?
If our subject is a little bit more complex or the background is a little bit more difficult, we can actually manually select the data we want to fill with.
Go edit, content aware fill.
Here you can choose what data is used to remove subjects.
We can change the opacity of our selection here and the colour if it clashes with our image so I'm going to choose red.
Keep all these other settings as is for now.
This preview window will show you how the fill will look with the info you have given it.
This is looking great.
If I wanted to remove some of the selection or add to it, I simply select the brushes at the top and hold alt and right click as you slide your mouse to change the size of your brush.
I'm going to remove everything except the beach around this young girl to make sure it doesn't sample from it.
My preview looks great so I'm going to hit ok.
Again, perfectly blends the image to remove the subject.
For our final step, let me show you how to touch up your removals so that they're always seamless.
Let's follow this process again with a more complex removal of this blanket that touches our other subject who is the main focus.
Again, we remove anything we don't want to sample from, so anything that isn't the backdrop must be removed.
Then we hit ok.
Highlight both layers, ctrl j to duplicate them, then ctrl e to merge them.
Let's choose the clone stamp tool.
And now we're going to set the flow to less than 5 and a low opacity to help us blend.
Here we hold alt and click to choose our reference point.
Then wherever we next click, hold and paint, we'll paint from our reference point, the little plus, so we can blend.
Did you see that?
I went too wide and my plus started referencing my subject to paint with.
To avoid this from happening, make smaller brush strokes and take your time.
I slowly painted the center and worked my way out until I had a gradient I was happy with.
Constantly using the alt click to get a new reference point, trying to always focus on a natural blend, setting my flow low to help me do this.
Now you have touched up the removal and look how seamless it is with this beautiful photo.
If you want more Photoshop in 5 content, other tutorials and amazing works, hit the subscribe button and follow Photoshop.
And as always, keep creating.

steps: Select the object to remove using one of the selection tools: Quick Selection Tool, Lasso Tool, Polygonal Lasso Tool, Quick Mask Mode, or Pen Tool.
If needed, expand the selection by going to Select > Modify > Expand to ensure there's space around the object.
Use Content-Aware Fill to remove the object: Press Ctrl + Backspace, set contents to Content-Aware Fill, and click OK.

Touch up the removal using the Clone Stamp Tool: Set flow to less than 5 and low opacity, hold Alt and click to set a reference point, and paint to blend the area seamlessly.

subgoal_summaries.title: Select Object-1
outcome: Object selected for removal
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Select the object to remove using one of the selection tools: Quick Selection Tool, Lasso Tool, Polygonal Lasso Tool, Quick Mask Mode, or Pen Tool.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Selecting the object is necessary to isolate it for removal.
subgoal_summaries.tips: For the Quick Selection Tool, ensure there is space around the object for best results. For the Lasso Tool, use a steady hand. Use the spacebar to move the canvas while selecting. Adjust brush size in Quick Mask Mode using alt and right-click. For the Pen Tool, use alt to adjust curves and straight lines.

subgoal_summaries.title: Refine Selection-2
outcome: The selection is expanded to include space around the object.
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Go to Select > Modify > Expand.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Expanding the selection ensures there's space around the object, making the filling process smoother.
subgoal_summaries.tips: The number for expansion depends on the image size; 15 is suggested for the example image.

subgoal_summaries.title: Remove Object-3
outcome: Unwanted object is removed from the image using Content-Aware Fill
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Press Ctrl + Backspace to bring up the fill panel, set contents to Content-Aware Fill, ensure color adaptation is ticked, and click OK.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: This process allows Photoshop to automatically fill the selected area by analyzing the surrounding pixels, effectively removing the unwanted object.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Ensure color adaptation is ticked for better blending results.

subgoal_summaries.title: Review and Adjust-4
outcome: Manually adjusted Content-Aware Fill settings for complex backgrounds
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Go to Edit > Content-Aware Fill. Choose the data to use for filling. Adjust the opacity and color of the selection if needed. Use the preview window to see the fill result. Use brushes to add or remove from the selection. Hit OK to apply the fill.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Manually selecting the data for Content-Aware Fill allows for better results with complex backgrounds or subjects.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Keep the other settings as is unless necessary. Use the preview window to ensure the fill looks correct before applying. Make sure to remove any areas from the selection that should not be sampled.

subgoal_summaries.title: Touch Up-5
outcome: Seamless blending of the area where the object was removed
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Set the flow to less than 5 and a low opacity on the Clone Stamp Tool. Hold Alt and click to set a reference point. Then, click, hold, and paint to blend the area seamlessly.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Setting a low flow and opacity helps in blending the area smoothly. Using Alt to set a reference point allows you to paint from a specific area to achieve a natural blend.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Make smaller brush strokes and take your time to avoid referencing unwanted areas. Constantly use Alt-click to get a new reference point for a natural blend.

steps: Open Photoshop and load the image you want to edit.
Select the Lasso Tool by pressing 'L' on your keyboard.
Use the Lasso Tool to draw a selection around the object you want to remove.
Go to the 'Edit' menu and select 'Content-Aware Fill'.
In the Content-Aware Fill workspace, you will see the selected area and a preview of the fill result.
On the left side, the green overlay shows the areas Photoshop will sample from to fill the selection.
Use the Eraser Tool to remove areas from the green overlay that you don't want Photoshop to sample from.
Ensure that only the areas you want to use for sampling are highlighted in green.
Check the preview on the right to see the result of the content-aware fill.
Once satisfied with the result, choose to output the fill to a new layer.
Click 'OK' to apply the changes and remove the object from the image.

steps: Open the image in Photoshop.
Select the Spot Healing Brush Tool from the toolbar.
Paint over the object you want to remove and observe the result.
If the result is unsatisfactory, save it as a snapshot in the History panel.
Use the Polygonal Lasso Tool to make a selection around the object.
Go to Edit > Content-Aware Fill and apply the default settings.
Deselect the selection using Ctrl or Command + D and save the result as a history state.
To use the new Remove Tool, ensure you have the Photoshop Beta version installed from the Creative Cloud Beta Apps section.
Select the Remove Tool from the Healing group in the toolbar.
Paint over the object you want to remove and observe the result.
If needed, paint over any remaining artifacts to fix them.
For nondestructive editing, create a new layer and enable 'Sample All Layers' in the Remove Tool options.
Use 'Remove After Each Stroke' for immediate fixes or leave it unchecked to apply changes after multiple strokes.
For complex areas, use selections to protect certain parts of the image before using the Remove Tool.
Compare results using the History panel to see the effectiveness of different tools.

subgoal_summaries.title: Touch Up-1
outcome: Object is removed from the image
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Paint over the object you want to remove.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: The Spot Healing Brush Tool automatically blends the painted area with the surrounding pixels to remove the object.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Ensure the entire object is properly covered while painting to achieve the best result.

subgoal_summaries.title: Review and Adjust-2
outcome: The current state of the image is saved as a snapshot in the History panel.
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Open the History panel and click on the button to create a snapshot.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Saving a snapshot allows you to preserve the current state of your work, so you can easily revert back to it if needed.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Ensure that the History panel is open and visible to quickly access the snapshot feature.

subgoal_summaries.title: Select Object-3
materials: Image with an object to be removed
outcome: A selection around the object to be removed
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Use the Polygonal Lasso Tool to make a selection around the object you want to remove.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Making a selection around the object isolates it, allowing you to apply further editing tools like Content Aware Fill without affecting other parts of the image.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Ensure the selection closely follows the edges of the object for a more accurate removal.

subgoal_summaries.title: Remove Object-4
materials: Image with an object to be removed
outcome: The object is removed from the image using Content-Aware Fill
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Go to Edit > Content-Aware Fill and apply the default settings, then hit OK.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Using Content-Aware Fill allows Photoshop to intelligently fill in the selected area by analyzing the surrounding pixels, which can result in a more seamless removal of the object.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Ensure the selection is accurate around the object to be removed for the best results.

subgoal_summaries.title: Review and Adjust-2
outcome: The selection is deselected and the result is saved as a history state
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Press Ctrl or Command + D to deselect the selection, then save the result as a history state by going to History and clicking on the button to create a snapshot.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Deselecting the selection allows you to see the final result without the selection outline, and saving it as a history state allows you to compare it with other edits or revert back to it if needed.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Make sure to save the history state after deselecting to keep a record of the changes.

subgoal_summaries.title: Touch Up-1
outcome: Object is removed from the image
Any remaining artifacts are fixed
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Select the Remove Tool from the Healing group in the toolbar. Paint over the object you want to remove and observe the result. If needed, paint over any remaining artifacts to fix them.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: The Remove Tool is used to seamlessly remove objects from an image by painting over them. It automatically fills in the area with surrounding content, making it appear as if the object was never there. If the initial removal leaves artifacts, painting over them again can fix these issues.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Ensure the entire object is covered when painting to achieve the best result. If the result is not perfect, try painting over the area again to improve it.

subgoal_summaries.title: Review and Adjust-2
outcome: Ability to compare the effectiveness of different object removal tools
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Open the History panel and create snapshots of the image after using each tool. Compare the snapshots to evaluate the effectiveness of each tool.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Creating snapshots allows you to save the state of the image after using each tool, enabling you to compare the results and determine which tool performed the best.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Ensure that you label each snapshot clearly to avoid confusion when comparing results.

subgoal_summaries.title: Touch Up-1
outcome: Photoshop Beta version installed and ready to use
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Open your Creative Cloud application, go to the Beta Apps section, and click on the Install button next to Photoshop Beta.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: This feature is only available in the beta version of Photoshop, so you need to install it to access the new Remove Tool.
subgoal_summaries.tips: If you're using a pirated version of Photoshop, you might not be able to access this feature.

subgoal_summaries.title: Nondestructive Editing-9
materials: Photoshop with the Remove Tool available
An image with objects to remove
outcome: The object is removed from the image nondestructively
The filled area is on a separate layer
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Create a new layer and enable 'Sample All Layers' in the Remove Tool options. Then, paint over the object you want to remove.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Enabling 'Sample All Layers' allows the tool to sample from all visible layers but apply the changes only to the new layer, ensuring nondestructive editing.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Ensure 'Sample All Layers' is checked to avoid making changes directly on the original image layer.

subgoal_summaries.title: Touch Up-1
materials: Photoshop with the Remove Tool feature
outcome: Immediate fixes after each stroke when 'Remove After Each Stroke' is checked
Ability to apply changes after multiple strokes when 'Remove After Each Stroke' is unchecked
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Use 'Remove After Each Stroke' for immediate fixes or leave it unchecked to apply changes after multiple strokes.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: When 'Remove After Each Stroke' is turned on, the tool applies the fix immediately after each stroke. When it is turned off, you can make multiple strokes and apply the fix all at once, which can be useful for more complex edits.
subgoal_summaries.tips: For small repairs, check 'Remove After Each Stroke' to fix issues immediately. For larger areas, leave it unchecked to refine the area with multiple strokes before applying the fix.

subgoal_summaries.title: Protect Areas-11
outcome: Protected parts of the image remain intact while removing unwanted objects
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Use the quick selection tool to make a selection around the area you want to protect. Then, use the Remove Tool to paint over the object you want to remove.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Making a selection prevents the Remove Tool from affecting the protected areas, ensuring that only the unwanted object is removed.
subgoal_summaries.tips: For complex areas where two objects are attached, use the Content Aware Fill instead of the Remove Tool for better results.

steps: Open the image in Photoshop.
Use the Pen tool (shortcut P) to create a precise selection around the object you want to remove.
Save the path for future use by going to the Paths tab and renaming the work path.
Convert the path to a selection by holding Ctrl (or Command) and clicking on the path thumbnail.
Feather the selection by going to Select > Modify > Feather and applying a 1-2 pixel feather.
Create a new layer and use the Clone Stamp tool to sample an area and paint over the object within the selection.
Deselect the selection by pressing Ctrl (or Command) D.
Define the perspective by creating a new layer and going to Filter > Vanishing Point.
Use the Create Plane tool to mark the four corners of the area with perspective.
Use the Clone tool within the Vanishing Point dialog to clone areas while maintaining perspective.
Adjust Clone tool settings such as diameter, hardness, and healing as needed.
Clone in small sections to maintain control and smoothness.
Use the Polygonal Lasso tool to select any remaining areas to fix.
Feather the selection and use the Clone Stamp tool to paint over these areas.
Deselect the selection and review the image for any remaining defects.
Make final adjustments and save your work.

subgoals.text: All right, once you have created the path, I would highly recommend to save it for later because who knows, maybe you might need it. So go to the Paths tab right here. subgoals.text: So with the Clone Stamp tool selected on a brand new layer, make sure you are in the Layers panel, just take a sample from above the plant and start painting right here. That's all you got to do. And we have that taken care of.

subgoals.title: Maintain Perspective-5
subgoals.text: Step number two is defining the perspective. Before you start to remove this stuff right over here, we need to define what the perspective is. So for me, it would be Removing the Easy Stuff. Now let's create a new layer on top of that and let's name this Perspective Removal. This is where we will define the perspective. Go to Filter and then Vanishing Point. Just zoom in and with the Create Plane tool, the shortcut to which is C, just mark along the four corners of the table. Now adjust these points and make sure they are positioned accurately. Now even though everything is so well aligned, there's still a gap right there. Because in the real world, my friend, things are just a little twisted, uneven or bent. Just like my right nostril is a little bigger than my left one or the vice versa. I don't really remember. But now that you have defined the perspective, everything you do inside it in this dialog box will maintain the perspective. For example, even if you try to paint with something, so let's say I'm painting with white, it maintains the perspective. The further we take it, the smaller it becomes. The closer we bring it, the larger it becomes. And it adjusts its shape according to the perspective. Let's go back by pressing Ctrl or Command Z. Now it's time for us to move to step number three, which some of you might have already guessed and that is Cloning in Perspective. If you have not noticed yet, there's also a Clone tool that you can work with in the perspective. And in here, if you try to clone, the lines will match up.
original_steps: Define the perspective by creating a new layer and going to Filter > Vanishing Point.
Use the Create Plane tool to mark the four corners of the area with perspective.
Use the Clone tool within the Vanishing Point dialog to clone areas while maintaining perspective.

subgoals.title: Adjust Removal-6
subgoals.text: Now in the Clone settings, there are some options. Diameter is simply the size of the brush. Hardness is simply the hardness of the brush. We want it to be absolutely soft. So we keep the hardness at zero. Opacity is the opacity of the brush. And this is an important one. Do you want to turn on the Healing or do you want to keep it off? So what does Healing do? To understand this, let's first learn what Healing does not do. So if you turn off Healing, now when you try to sample from a place by holding the Alt key or the Option key, click to take a sample, and then now you try to paint something right here, okay, it is just a simple copy paste with a brush. It doesn't change its texture, color or anything. It doesn't try to adjust, just like the Clone Stamp tool. It's a dumb tool that just copies and pastes in a brush. That's all there is to it. However, if you turn on the Healing, now when you try to take a sample, and now when you paint right over here, and when you release your mouse, it'll try to match up. It did a pretty bad job because we didn't cover everything, but it tries to match up. And sometimes dumb works better because then it's just straightforward and we have complete control over it. So in this case, we're just going to turn off Healing.
original_steps: Adjust Clone tool settings such as diameter, hardness, and healing as needed.

subgoals.title: Maintain Perspective-7
subgoals.text: We want it to be dumb so that we can control them. subgoals.title: Touch Up-8

We can fix the top area later. Now let's do this area. Some areas are still a little dark. No problem. Let's take a sample from right here and this time we want to do a little bit of matching. So let's turn on Healing and try to cover over it. There you go. Let's leave it. It'll try to match it up and it has done a pretty good job. Press Ctrl or Command 0 to just fit the canvas to the screen and there you go. It's pretty much removed. Hit OK once you're satisfied. The problem is still not completely solved. Have a look. There is this area still left out. We need to fix that. It's simple. Select the Polygonal Lasso tool and let's make a selection of that area. To keep it smooth, just give it a little feather by going to Select and then Modify Feather. One pixel is fine. Hit OK and then with the help of the Clone Stamp tool, just take a sample by holding the Alt key or the Option key. Click to take a sample. Make sure Sample Current and Below is selected and then just paint.
original_steps: Clone in small sections to maintain control and smoothness.
Use the Polygonal Lasso tool to select any remaining areas to fix.
Feather the selection and use the Clone Stamp tool to paint over these areas.

subgoals.title: Review and Adjust-9
subgoals.text: Easily fixed. Press Ctrl or Command D to deselect and there you go.

subgoals.title: Save Work-10
subgoals.text: That's how to remove objects placed on complex perspectives with Photoshop. Let's do a quick little recap. Step number one, remove the easy stuff with the help of the Clone Stamp tool or the Healing Brush tool, the Patch tool, whichever is your favorite. Step number two, define the perspective by going to Filter and then Vanishing Point. Just define the plane. If you keep it turned on, it'll try to match the cloned area with the surrounding areas. If you keep it turned off, it is just a simple copy and paste in a brush, just like the Clone Stamp tool. Step number four is simply finishing touches, removing little defects here and there. And that's all there is to it. So that's all for this video. subgoal_summaries.title: Open Image-0
outcome: Image is opened in Photoshop
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Open the image file in Photoshop.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Opening the image in Photoshop is necessary to begin editing and removing objects from it.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Ensure that Photoshop is installed and updated to the latest version for best performance.

subgoal_summaries.title: Select Object-1
outcome: A precise path around the object to be removed
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Use the Pen tool to create a precise selection around the object you want to remove.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Creating a precise selection ensures that the object can be removed cleanly without affecting surrounding areas.
subgoal_summaries.tips: To turn a curve into a corner, hold the Alt or Option key and click on it. Click and drag to draw a curve. Adjust points by holding Ctrl or Command. Save the path for later use by renaming it in the Paths tab.

subgoal_summaries.title: Refine Selection-2
materials: Path created with the Pen tool
outcome: Path is saved for future use
Path is converted to a selection
Selection is feathered for a softer edge
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Save the path for future use by going to the Paths tab and renaming the work path. Convert the path to a selection by holding Ctrl (or Command) and clicking on the path thumbnail. Feather the selection by going to Select > Modify > Feather and applying a 1-2 pixel feather.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Saving the path allows you to reuse it later without having to recreate it. Feathering the selection softens the edges, preventing sharp transitions when applying edits.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Ensure the Paths tab is visible by checking it under the Window menu. Adjust the feather value based on the image resolution for optimal results.

subgoal_summaries.title: Remove Object-3
materials: Image with object to be removed
outcome: Object removed from the image
Smooth transition in the area where the object was removed
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Create a new layer, select the Clone Stamp tool, take a sample from an area above the object, and paint over the object within the selection.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Using a new layer allows for non-destructive editing, and the Clone Stamp tool helps in covering the object by sampling similar areas.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Ensure the selection is feathered to avoid sharp edges and achieve a smooth blend.

subgoal_summaries.title: Review and Adjust-4
outcome: The selection is deselected, allowing you to proceed with other tasks without affecting the selected area.
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Press Ctrl or Command D to deselect.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Deselecting the selection allows you to proceed with other tasks without affecting the selected area.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Be careful not to deselect if you might need the selection again soon, unless you have saved the path.

subgoal_summaries.title: Maintain Perspective-5
materials: Image with objects to be removed
outcome: Perspective defined for accurate object removal
Objects removed while maintaining perspective
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Create a new layer and go to Filter > Vanishing Point. Use the Create Plane tool to mark the four corners of the area with perspective. Use the Clone tool within the Vanishing Point dialog to clone areas while maintaining perspective.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Defining the perspective ensures that any cloning or painting done within the Vanishing Point dialog maintains the correct perspective, making the object removal look natural.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Ensure the Create Plane tool accurately marks the corners for correct perspective. Use a soft brush with zero hardness for cloning. Turn off Healing for more control over the cloning process.

subgoal_summaries.title: Adjust Removal-6
materials: Image with objects to be removed
outcome: Clone tool settings adjusted for optimal object removal
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Adjust the Clone tool settings by setting the diameter to control the brush size, setting the hardness to zero for a soft brush, and deciding whether to turn on or off the Healing option based on the desired effect.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: The diameter controls the size of the brush, hardness controls the softness of the brush edges, and the Healing option determines whether the cloned area will blend with the surrounding area or simply copy the sampled area.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Keep the hardness at zero for a soft edge and turn off Healing for more control over the cloning process.

subgoal_summaries.title: Maintain Perspective-5
materials: Image with objects to be removed
outcome: Objects removed from the image while maintaining perspective
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Use the Clone tool within the Vanishing Point dialog to clone areas while maintaining perspective. Hold the Alt key or the Option key, click to take a sample, and then start painting. Match up the lines, make sure everything is aligned, and then start painting. Do bit by bit to keep the tone smoother.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Cloning in perspective ensures that the lines and proportions remain consistent with the image's perspective, making the removal seamless.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Avoid doing all at once. Doing bit by bit gives you more control over it and keeps the tone smoother. Make the brush smaller if needed to avoid bringing up the edge of the path.
tools: Clone tool within the Vanishing Point dialog

subgoal_summaries.title: Touch Up-8
materials: Image with objects to be removed
outcome: Remaining areas are fixed and blended smoothly with the surrounding image
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Use the Polygonal Lasso tool to select any remaining areas to fix. Feather the selection and use the Clone Stamp tool to paint over these areas.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Feathering the selection helps to blend the cloned area smoothly with the surrounding pixels, avoiding harsh edges.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Clone in small sections to maintain control and smoothness.

subgoal_summaries.title: Review and Adjust-4
outcome: The selection is removed from the image, allowing for a clear view of the edited area.
The image is reviewed for any remaining defects after deselecting.
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Press Ctrl or Command D to deselect the selection.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Deselecting the selection allows you to see the image without the selection outline, making it easier to review the image for any remaining defects.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Ensure that you have completed all necessary edits within the selection before deselecting, as it can be cumbersome to recreate the selection if needed again.

subgoal_summaries.title: Save Work-10
outcome: Final image with objects removed and saved
subgoal_summaries.instructions: Make final adjustments to remove any remaining defects using tools like the Clone Stamp tool or Healing Brush tool. Once satisfied with the result, save your work.
subgoal_summaries.explanation: Final adjustments ensure that all small defects are corrected, resulting in a polished image. Saving the work preserves the changes made.
subgoal_summaries.tips: Use a feathered selection to keep edges smooth when making final adjustments. Save your work in a format that preserves layers for future editing.

steps: Open the image in Photoshop.
Select the object you want to remove using the Quick Selection Tool or Lasso Tool.
Duplicate the layer to keep a clean copy of the original image.
Use Content-Aware Fill to remove the selected object:
- Press Shift + Delete (Shift + Backspace on Windows) to open the Fill dialog box.
- Choose Content-Aware and click OK.
If the result is not satisfactory, use the Content-Aware Fill workspace:
- Go to Edit > Content-Aware Fill.
- Use the masking tool to exclude unwanted areas from the sample.
- Adjust the selection area using the Lasso Tool if needed.
- Click OK to apply the changes and deselect with Ctrl + D.
For moving objects, use the Content-Aware Move Tool:
- Select the object with the Lasso Tool.
- Drag the object to a new position and press Enter to apply.
Use the Clone Stamp Tool for fine-tuning:
- Create a new layer and set the Clone Stamp Tool to 'Current and Below'.
- Alt-click (Option-click on Mac) to sample an area and paint over artifacts.
For removing straight lines like power lines, use the Spot Healing Brush Tool:
- Create a new layer and enable 'Sample All Layers'.
- Click at the start of the line, hold Shift, and click at the end to remove it.
For removing braces or small details, use the Brush Tool:
- Create a new layer and sample the color of the area to paint over.
- Use a soft brush with low hardness and adjust opacity for blending.
- Paint over the area, sampling colors as needed to blend smoothly.

metadata.title: How to remove ANYTHING from a photo in Photoshop. 3 WAYS!

subgoal_definitions.title: Open Image
subgoal_definitions.description: Open the image in Photoshop to begin the editing process.
original_steps: Open the image in Photoshop.
Open the image in Photoshop.
Open the image in Photoshop.
Open Photoshop and load the image you want to edit.
Open the image in Photoshop.

subgoal_definitions.title: Select Object
subgoal_definitions.description: Select the object to be removed using a selection tool.
original_steps: Select the object you want to remove using the Quick Selection Tool or Lasso Tool.
Use the Pen tool (shortcut P) to create a precise selection around the object you want to remove.
Use the Polygonal Lasso Tool to make a selection around the object.
Select the Lasso Tool by pressing 'L' on your keyboard.
Use the Lasso Tool to draw a selection around the object you want to remove.
Select the object to remove using one of the selection tools: Quick Selection Tool, Lasso Tool, Polygonal Lasso Tool, Quick Mask Mode, or Pen Tool.
Select the Lasso tool by pressing 'L' on your keyboard or finding it in the toolbar.
Create a selection around the object you want to remove, leaving some space around it.

subgoal_definitions.title: Refine Selection
subgoal_definitions.description: Ensure the selection is precise and has some space around the object.
original_steps: Save the path for future use by going to the Paths tab and renaming the work path.
Convert the path to a selection by holding Ctrl (or Command) and clicking on the path thumbnail.
Feather the selection by going to Select > Modify > Feather and applying a 1-2 pixel feather.
If needed, expand the selection by going to Select > Modify > Expand to ensure there's space around the object.
Set the feather to 10 pixels and ensure Anti-Aliased is checked in the Options bar.

subgoal_definitions.title: Duplicate Layer
subgoal_definitions.description: Duplicate the layer to keep a clean copy of the original image for nondestructive editing.
original_steps: Duplicate the layer to keep a clean copy of the original image.

subgoal_definitions.title: Remove Object
subgoal_definitions.description: Use a removal method to eliminate the object from the image.
original_steps: Use Content-Aware Fill to remove the selected object: - Press Shift + Delete (Shift + Backspace on Windows) to open the Fill dialog box. - Choose Content-Aware and click OK.
For moving objects, use the Content-Aware Move Tool: - Select the object with the Lasso Tool. - Drag the object to a new position and press Enter to apply.
Create a new layer and use the Clone Stamp tool to sample an area and paint over the object within the selection.
Go to Edit > Content-Aware Fill and apply the default settings.
Go to the 'Edit' menu and select 'Content-Aware Fill'.
Use Content-Aware Fill to remove the object: Press Ctrl + Backspace, set contents to Content-Aware Fill, and click OK.
Click on 'Generative Fill' in the Contextual taskbar and then click 'Generate' without adding a prompt.

subgoal_definitions.title: Adjust Removal
subgoal_definitions.description: Adjust settings or sampling areas in the removal tool workspace and check the preview.
original_steps: If the result is not satisfactory, use the Content-Aware Fill workspace: - Go to Edit > Content-Aware Fill. - Use the masking tool to exclude unwanted areas from the sample. - Adjust the selection area using the Lasso Tool if needed. - Click OK to apply the changes and deselect with Ctrl + D.
Adjust Clone tool settings such as diameter, hardness, and healing as needed.
In the Content-Aware Fill workspace, you will see the selected area and a preview of the fill result.
On the left side, the green overlay shows the areas Photoshop will sample from to fill the selection.
Use the Eraser Tool to remove areas from the green overlay that you don't want Photoshop to sample from.
Ensure that only the areas you want to use for sampling are highlighted in green.
Check the preview on the right to see the result of the content-aware fill.

subgoal_definitions.title: Nondestructive Editing
subgoal_definitions.description: Create a new layer and enable 'Sample All Layers' for nondestructive editing.
original_steps: For nondestructive editing, create a new layer and enable 'Sample All Layers' in the Remove Tool options.

subgoal_definitions.title: Touch Up
subgoal_definitions.description: Use additional tools to touch up and blend the area seamlessly.
original_steps: Use the Clone Stamp Tool for fine-tuning: - Create a new layer and set the Clone Stamp Tool to 'Current and Below'. - Alt-click (Option-click on Mac) to sample an area and paint over artifacts.

For removing straight lines like power lines, use the Spot Healing Brush Tool: - Create a new layer and enable 'Sample All Layers'. - Click at the start of the line, hold Shift, and click at the end to remove it.

For removing braces or small details, use the Brush Tool: - Create a new layer and sample the color of the area to paint over. - Use a soft brush with low hardness and adjust opacity for blending. - Paint over the area, sampling colors as needed to blend smoothly.
Clone in small sections to maintain control and smoothness.
Use the Polygonal Lasso tool to select any remaining areas to fix.
Feather the selection and use the Clone Stamp tool to paint over these areas.
Select the Spot Healing Brush Tool from the toolbar.
Paint over the object you want to remove and observe the result.
To use the new Remove Tool, ensure you have the Photoshop Beta version installed from the Creative Cloud Beta Apps section.
Select the Remove Tool from the Healing group in the toolbar.
Paint over the object you want to remove and observe the result.
Use 'Remove After Each Stroke' for immediate fixes or leave it unchecked to apply changes after multiple strokes.
If needed, paint over any remaining artifacts to fix them.
Touch up the removal using the Clone Stamp Tool: Set flow to less than 5 and low opacity, hold Alt and click to set a reference point, and paint to blend the area seamlessly.
For smaller areas, use the Remove tool by creating a new layer and enabling 'Sample All Layers'.
Paint over the areas you want to remove with the Remove tool and press Enter to apply changes.
Use the Remove tool to touch up any remaining areas outside the selection.

subgoal_definitions.title: Protect Areas
subgoal_definitions.description: Use selections to protect certain parts of the image before using removal tools.
original_steps: For complex areas, use selections to protect certain parts of the image before using the Remove Tool.

subgoal_definitions.title: Maintain Perspective
subgoal_definitions.description: Use perspective tools to maintain perspective while cloning.
original_steps: Define the perspective by creating a new layer and going to Filter > Vanishing Point.
Use the Create Plane tool to mark the four corners of the area with perspective.
Use the Clone tool within the Vanishing Point dialog to clone areas while maintaining perspective.

subgoal_definitions.title: Review and Adjust
subgoal_definitions.description: Review the result and make final adjustments to ensure the image looks seamless.
original_steps: Deselect the selection by pressing Ctrl (or Command) D.
Deselect the selection and review the image for any remaining defects.
If the result is unsatisfactory, save it as a snapshot in the History panel.
Deselect the selection using Ctrl or Command + D and save the result as a history state.
Compare results using the History panel to see the effectiveness of different tools.
Once satisfied with the result, choose to output the fill to a new layer.
Click 'OK' to apply the changes and remove the object from the image.
For complex backgrounds, manually adjust the Content-Aware Fill settings by going to Edit > Content-Aware Fill and selecting the data to use for filling.
Review the variations provided and select the one that looks best.
